visions","id":"49753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49753"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to his General Practice clinic with his mother who is concerned about his difficulty keeping up with his peers when running and climbing. He has been slow to reach motor milestones. He has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has calf pseudohypertrophy and Gower\u0027s sign is positive. Investigations reveal creatine kinase 15,000 U/L (30-200).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the genetic basis of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Missense mutation in the dystrophin gene","Expansion of a trinucleotide repeat","Deletion in the dystrophin gene causing a frameshift","Mutation in a gene encoding a sarcoplasmic reticulum protein","Duplication in the alpha-actinin gene"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD) is an X-linked recessive disorder caused by mutations in the DMD \u003Cstrong\u003Egene\u003C/strong\u003E that encodes \u003Cstrong\u003Edystrophin\u003C/strong\u003E. Dystrophin is a cytoskeletal protein that helps stabilise the  sarcolemma (muscle fibre membrane) during muscular contraction. In the absence of functional dystrophin, muscle fibres are prone to damage, leading to cycles of necrosis and regeneration, and eventual replacement of muscle with fatty and fibrous tissue. The majority (60-70%) of DMD cases are due to \u003Cstrong\u003Edeletions\u003C/strong\u003E within the DMD gene. Most of the remainder are due to small mutations or duplications. These mutations disrupt the reading frame, leading to a truncated, non-functional dystrophin protein. In-frame deletions that allow production of a partially functional dystrophin protein lead to the milder Becker muscular dystrophy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Emissense mutations\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ein the dystrophin gene\u003C/strong\u003E can occur, they are much less common than deletions or duplications. Missense mutations do not typically cause the severe phenotype seen in DMD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDMD is not caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Etrinucleotide repeat expansions\u003C/strong\u003E. These are responsible for a different group of disorders including Huntington disease and myotonic dystrophy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMutations in genes encoding\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Esarcoplasmic reticulum\u003C/strong\u003E proteins like the ryanodine receptor (RYR1) are associated with a different group of muscle disorders, the congenital myopathies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-actinin\u003C/strong\u003E is another component of the muscle cytoskeleton, but mutations in this gene have not been associated with muscular dystrophy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Duchenne muscular dystrophy is an X-linked recessive disorder caused by mutations in the DMD gene that encodes dystrophin.","Dystrophin is a cytoskeletal protein that stabilises muscle fibres during contraction. Its absence leads to muscle damage and weakness.","Most cases are due to deletions or duplications within the DMD gene that disrupt the reading frame and lead to a truncated, non-functional dystrophin protein."],"references":["Darras BT. Duchenne and Becker muscular dystrophy: Clinical features and diagnosis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/duchenne-and-becker-muscular-dystrophy-clinical-features-and-diagnosis","Nowak KJ, Davies KE. Duchenne muscular dystrophy and dystrophin: pathogenesis and opportunities for treatment. EMBO Rep. 2004 Sep;5(9):872-6. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1299132/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35007"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13737"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35007"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-03T16:19:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T20:54:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6356"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49753"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{